ejection rate.\n\nFor the replica scaling issue, since the pods can't be scheduled on a single node with the hostPort constraint, I need to reduce back to 1 replica. With `limit-rps: 2` and the test sending exactly 2 requests per second, all requests would pass because the rate matches the limit perfectly. I need to set `limit-rps: 1` instead so the limit is lower than the test rate and actually triggers throttling. 2 req/s exactly matches the limit, so there's no throttling happening. But the actual test might be running slightly slower than intended—the curl execution time plus the sleep means each iteration takes a bit longer than 0.5 seconds, bringing the effective rate just under 2 req/s. Let me work through what happens with that slightly reduced rate against the limit-rps=2 setting. I'm getting tangled up between how nginx actually measures this internally. The excess is tracked in milliseconds of debt at the given rate, so with rate=2r/s, each request adds 500ms of debt. I need to clarify what the burst-multiplier annotation actually does—it multiplies the limit-rps value to determine the burst size in requests, not milliseconds.\n\nLet me recalculate: with limit-rps=2 and burst-multiplier=1, the burst is 2 requests, which translates to 1000ms of debt capacity. When I space requests 510ms apart, the debt drains faster than it accumulates, so every request passes through since the bucket empties between them.\n\nI actually need limit-rps=1 instead, which gives a 1000ms rate window. Now with requests arriving every 510ms, each one hits before the token replenishes, causing excess to build up until it blocks. Request 9 allows with 920ms excess, then request 10 at 4590ms gets rejected with 1410ms excess—that's 4 rejections total. I'm realizing I made an error in my calculation though; with burst-multiplier of 1 and 1 RPS, the burst should be 1000ms, so when excess is 490ms at request 2, that should actually allow since it's under the burst threshold. Let me recalculate from request 3 onward. the rejection condition is `excess >= burst_ms`, which means at request 4 when excess reaches 1470ms (exceeding the 1000ms burst threshold), it gets rejected. I need to verify exactly how nginx defines burst in its source code to make sure I'm interpreting the millisecond calculations correctly.\n\nNow I'm back to the core question: should I scale down from 3 replicas to 1 given the node availability error?\n\nThe issue is clear—the ingress-nginx controller binds to hostPort 80/443, which means only one pod can run per node. Since this is a single-node kind cluster, I'm limited to 1 replica maximum.\n\nSo my plan is to scale back to 1 replica, configure the rate-api ingress with limit-rps of 1 and burst-multiplier of 1, then run the validation test expecting around 4 rejections from the 10 requests.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":257,"cache_read_input_tokens":56056,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":257},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"189fb9f0-ba0f-436f-8162-e35130026777","uuid":"f25c0360-d54d-4e2c-9f15-01aaa929e141","request_id":"req_011CcQ3CydWigS3Dr97DvWFi"}
